string.text:
Language definitions consist of mapping an internal ID (eg: "ADD_PLAYLIST") to the actual text to be displayed. The text may contain a limited number of markup tags which are indicated by square brackets and perform an identical function to their HTML counterparts.
[p]The following tags are supported: [ul] [li]&#91;br&#93; - A line break[/li] [li]&#91;p&#93;&#91;/p&#93; - A new paragraph[/li] [li]&#91;b&#93;&#91;/b&#93; - Bold[/li] [li]&#91;i&#93;&#91;/i&#93; - Italics[/li] [li]&#91;em&#93; and &#91;/em&#93; - Emphasis[/li] [li]&#91;ol&#93;&#91;/ol&#93; - An ordered list[/li] [li]&#91;ul&#93;&#91;/ul&#93; - An unordered list[/li] [li]&#91;li&#93;&#91;/li&#93; - A list item within an ordered or unordered list[/li] [/ul]
[p]In some circumstances, other text may need to be substituted within the text. Placeholders for the position within the string where the substitution occurs are indicated with '&#37;s'. For example, In the ID "MANY_TRACKS" the number of tracks that has been found within the database is substituted for the &#37;s within the string... so a search returning 4 tracks would be displayed to the user as "4 Tracks";
